Release blockers:
  ☐ Path-dep versions for crates.io - `Cargo.toml [workspace.dependencies]` references `bevy-react-animations` / `bevy-react-canvas` / `bevy-react-macros` by `path` only. crates.io rejects path-only deps — each needs `version = "0.1.0"` alongside `path`, and the leaf crates must be published first (macros → canvas/animations → core).
  ☐ npm publish model - `js/package.json` `exports` ship raw `./src/*.ts` (no build output). Confirm that's intended for the esbuild-bundling consumer, or add a build step and ship compiled JS + `.d.ts`.
  ☐ Add `CHANGELOG.md` and `CONTRIBUTING.md`
  ☐ stabilize API
    ☐ Mark the public wire enums `#[non_exhaustive]` (`crates/core/src/protocol.rs:33` `Op`, `:1320` `Outbound`). Both are pub via `pub mod protocol` ("exposed for advanced use"); adding a variant is semver-breaking for any downstream exhaustive `match`. Cheap pre-publish insurance.

Correctness:
  JS-input panics (extends the archived "Panic audit", which only checked `.unwrap()`/`.expect()`, not panicking library calls):
    ✔ `parse_grid_placement` panics the app on ordinary JS style (`crates/core/src/ui_map.rs`). `gridColumn:"0"`→`GridPlacement::start(0)`, `"span 0"`→`span(0)` panic Bevy 0.19's constructors (`try_into_grid_index` `.expect`s on 0, bevy_ui `ui_node.rs:2086`) → crashed the Update schedule. (NOTE: only ZERO panics — `"2 / 2"` is fine; the original "guard zero/equal" over-guarded.) Fixed: `try_grid_placement` tokenizes each component and any zero line/span (or unrecognized token) aborts the whole placement → `warn!` + `auto()` via `unknown_keyword`, never a partial placement like `"2 / 0"`→`start(2)`; also upgraded the previously-silent garbage fallback to a warn and added `"auto / 3"`→`end(3)` support. Tests: `grid_placement_zero_falls_back_to_auto` covers all six zero forms + garbage. @done(26-07-01)
    ✔ `AnchorScaling` min/max reach `f32::clamp` unchecked (`crates/core/src/anchor.rs`). Swapped bounds or a NaN bound panicked every frame; `factor:0` with `dist==0` gave `0*inf=NaN` scale. Fixed in two layers: `AnchorScaling::sanitized()` runs once at apply time (`apply_anchor`, reconcile.rs) — non-finite field → warn + disable scaling, `min>max` → warn + swap — and the per-frame math is extracted into `distance_scale()` which resolves a NaN product to `max` (closest → largest, matching the doc'd `inf` behavior). Tests in `anchor.rs::tests`. @done(26-07-01)
    ✔ Spring `stiffness`/`damping` used unclamped while `mass` is clamped (`crates/animations/src/lib.rs`). `withSpring({stiffness:-1})` (or `0`, or NaN) diverged to NaN / never settled → runner never dropped. Fixed: both now clamp to `1e-4` exactly like `mass` (`f32::max` maps NaN to the floor too). Test: `spring_survives_hostile_params` steps hostile springs to settlement asserting finiteness. @done(26-07-01)
  Behavior:
    ☐ Opacity overwrites base alpha instead of multiplying (`crates/animations/src/lib.rs:288`). Code does `s.alpha = alpha` but `protocol.rs:128` documents Opacity as "Multiplies color alpha"; a base `rgba(255,0,0,0.4)` with animated opacity `1.0` renders fully opaque. Fix to `s.alpha *= alpha` (or correct the doc if overwrite is intended).
    ☐ Pending request promises never rejected on reload/shutdown (`js/src/bridge.ts:476`). `case "reload": return;` and `msg == null` break exit `runEventLoop` without draining `pendingRequests`; since the isolate persists across hot reload, an in-flight `await bevy.*.get()` at reload time hangs forever. Reject all pending entries before returning/breaking.
    ☐ Dropped `Responder` hangs the JS promise forever (`crates/core/src/request.rs:65`). `Responder<R>` has no `Drop` impl that rejects: a handler that early-returns without responding (e.g. responds only on its success branch) or loses a deferred responder to a despawn never emits `Outbound::Response`, and `pendingRequests` (`js/src/bridge.ts:238`) has no timeout — `await bevy.foo()` blocks permanently. Unknown-name (`request.rs:262`) and malformed-payload (`:237`) paths both reject; this is the one Rust-side failure mode that hangs. Fix: `impl Drop for Responder` → send a `ResponseResult::Err` if `!done`.
    ☐ `onClick` fires on mouse-down, not press+release (`crates/core/src/reconcile.rs:1004`). Emitted on the `Changed<Interaction>` → `Pressed` transition with no release-side check, so press → drag off → release still clicks — diverges from the DOM semantics React authors expect and makes drag-away-to-cancel impossible. Fire on release while still `Hovered`/over the pressed node.
    ☐ `ariaLabel` is a silent no-op on `<button>`/`<node>`/`<image>` (`crates/core/src/reconcile.rs:728`). Only `<editableText>` gets an `AccessibilityNode` (`:310`), and the label-writing branch (`:519`) is gated on `editable_inputs`, so an icon-only `<button ariaLabel="Close">` announces nothing to screen readers. Insert an `AccessibilityNode` with a proper role for buttons/images and apply `ariaLabel` generically.
    ☐ `last_good_app` promoted before the refresh render is validated (`crates/core/src/js_thread.rs:316`). `last_good_app = new_code` the instant `execute_script("[app-update]")` returns Ok, but a bundle whose top-level IIFE runs clean can still fail its Fast-Refresh render (the error is swallowed by mount.ts's try/catch and the reconciler's `onUncaughtError`) — the UI survives, but the render-broken bundle becomes the `[app-restore]` fallback, defeating "known-good". Also untested: `crates/core/tests/hot_reload.rs` covers only the happy path — no test for `[app-restore]` or the top-level-Ok-but-render-throws case.
  Lower severity:
    ☐ Keyboard non-Character keys stringified via Rust `Debug` (`crates/core/src/keyboard.rs:66`) — Space becomes `"Space"` where the web `KeyboardEvent.key` contract is `" "`.
    ☐ ts-rs declaration dedup keys by type *name*, not `TypeId` (`crates/core/src/ts_codegen.rs:344`) — two distinct Rust types ts-rs names identically silently overwrite each other in generated `bevy.ts`.
    ☐ Event dispatch iterates the live listener `Set` (`js/src/bridge.ts:499`). Self-unsubscribe (the one-shot pattern) is safe, but a listener that removes a *different* not-yet-visited listener mid-dispatch skips it, and one added mid-dispatch fires within the same event. Snapshot before iterating (`for (const cb of [...set])`).

Performance:
  Quick wins (highest value first):
    ☐ `HANDLER_PROP_KEYS` is stale — 5 of 11 handlers (`js/src/renderer.ts:49`). Missing `onPointerEnter`/`onPointerLeave`/`onSelect`/`onFocus`/`onBlur`/`onScroll` fall into the `Object.is` branch, so their ever-changing closures make `bevyPropsChanged` always true → a full `update` op + re-serialize every parent re-render for nodes using them. Derive from `HANDLER_KINDS` (the documented dual-list drift gotcha).
    ☐ Settled opacity rewritten every frame (`crates/core/src/transition.rs:546`). When `style.opacity` is set but not transitioning, the block still does `tc.0 = tc.0.with_alpha(...)` (+bg/image) unconditionally, tripping `Changed<TextColor>`/`Changed<BackgroundColor>` forever → per-frame re-extraction. Skip the write when unchanged (set-if-neq, as `anchor.rs::set_visibility` does).
    ☐ `apply_style` bare-inserts paint components, marking them `Changed` when equal (`crates/core/src/ui_map.rs:834`). `FocusPolicy` is inserted unconditionally on every call, and `BackgroundColor`/`BorderColor`/`Outline`/`BoxShadow`/gradients/`ZIndex`/`GlobalZIndex` (`:725-816`) are re-inserted on every update — Bevy's `insert` always marks `Changed` regardless of equality. Every `Op::Update` AND every hover/press flip pays it (`apply_interaction_styles` → `apply_style`, `reconcile.rs:1443`). Mirror the `set_node_if_changed`/`set_if_neq` treatment `Node` already gets (`ui_map.rs:711`); independent of (and compounding with) deeper-perf #1.
    ☐ Reuse the ops buffer in `apply_js_ops` (`crates/core/src/reconcile.rs:126`). `let mut ops = Vec::new(); … ops.extend(batch)` allocates + copies every frame on the hottest path. Move the `Vec<Op>` into `JsBridge` and `std::mem::take` it out (drain+clear) to keep capacity across frames — `mem::take` hands back an owned Vec so the "don't hold the borrow" comment still holds.
    ☐ Gate the flush instrumentation (`js/src/bridge.ts:200`). `flush()` runs every commit (~60fps) yet unconditionally does two `nowMs()` calls + a fresh object alloc + a global write just so a benchmark host might read `__bevyReactFlush`. Wrap in a dev/flag check so production commits skip it. NOTE: the stress bench reads it (`examples/stress/ui/src/App.tsx:139`) — gate, don't delete. Also drop the two commented-out `console.log` scaffolding lines there.
    ☐ `on_focus_gained`/`on_focus_lost`: `ResMut<JsBridge>` → `Res<JsBridge>` (`crates/core/src/reconcile.rs:1162`). Neither mutates the bridge, so `Res` removes needless scheduler serialization. Free, but focus events are rare — cleanup, not measurable speed.
    ☐ `PointerCapture` written unconditionally every frame (`crates/core/src/reconcile.rs:1354`). `capture.dragging`/`capture.over_ui` are assigned each tick (plus a full `Interaction` scan) so the resource is `Changed` even when idle. No `Changed<PointerCapture>` consumer exists today, so the cost is just the scan + spurious tick — low; `set_if_neq` + deriving `over_ui` from `Changed<Interaction>` transitions is a one-line hardening.
  Deeper / architectural (ranked by payoff; best payoff-to-risk: #2 and #3, #1 is the biggest win but riskiest):
    ☐ 1. Partial/diffed `Op::Update` — kill update amplification (`crates/core/src/reconcile.rs:467`). Today JS `bevyPropsChanged` decides *whether* to update but sends the FULL prop set, and `apply_style` re-applies everything (rebuild `Node`, re-parse colors, re-insert transform, re-resolve text style) even for a one-prop change; `set_node_if_changed` saves the relayout but not the CPU. The reconciler already iterates changed keys — have it emit the delta and serialize only changed props. Invasive part: `apply_style` treats "field absent" as "remove/reset to default" (`background_color:None`→`remove::<BackgroundColor>()`), so partial updates must distinguish UNSET from UNCHANGED. Turns per-node update from O(all props) to O(changed). Headline of the "Update amplification" benchmark item.
    ☐ 2. Decode enum-like style fields into real enums at the serde boundary (`crates/core/src/protocol.rs:251` — TODO already there). ~25 `Option<String>` fields (`display`/`align*`/`justify*`/`overflow*`/`flex*`/`grid_*`) are re-string-matched by `node_from_style` every `Op::Update`, and `parse_template` re-allocs a `Vec<RepeatedGridTrack>` per grid axis. Give them typed enums + custom `Deserialize` that warns+falls back (preserving today's behavior), like `Length`/`Angle`/`Time`/`Rect` already do; `node_from_style` then becomes a plain field copy. Wire-type change → regenerate `bevy.ts`; warn+fallback logic moves from `ui_map` into the deserializers. Compounds with #1. Best payoff-to-risk (self-contained, no semantic change). Also collapses the 13 copy-paste `&str -> enum` keyword fns (`ui_map.rs:242-388`).
    ☐ 3. Batch the Bevy→JS event channel (`crates/core/src/js_thread.rs:118`). `op_next_event` resolves ONE `Outbound` per call → one Promise + one channel recv + one `runEventLoop` turn per event; under floods (per-frame events, pointer-move streams, request bursts) that's a promise per event. Add `op_next_events()` that drains up to N into a `Vec<Outbound>`; JS wraps the batch in one `flushSync`. Ties to the "event flood / backpressure" benchmark item and the unbounded-channel debt.
    ☐ 4. Single-deserialize `op_emit`/`op_request` (`crates/core/src/js_thread.rs:104`). `op_request` takes `#[serde] serde_json::Value`, ships it in `RawRequest`, then `request::dispatch` re-deserializes `Value→T` — two allocs + reparse per message vs `op_flush`'s direct v8→`Vec<Op>`. Op can't know `T` statically (name is runtime); fix is registry-driven deserialize-once, or keep raw bytes instead of a `Value` tree. Only matters if emit/request run per-frame (e.g. a slider emitting each frame).
    ☐ 5. Memoize `serializeProps` on unchanged style refs (`js/src/bridge.ts`). Every changed node rebuilds `style`/`animated`/`anchor` objects from scratch each commit; since styles are meant to be hoisted to stable module consts, cache the serialized form keyed by input-object identity and skip re-serialization when the ref is unchanged. Pure JS-side.
    ☐ 6. Canvas: reuse the finished path across fill+stroke (`crates/canvas/src/lib.rs:242`). `path.clone().finish()` per `Fill`/`Stroke` and `Paint` rebuilt per color cmd — a `… Fill, Stroke` pair clones the full point/verb buffer twice. Finish once into a reusable `Path`, reuse across the pair. Lowest difficulty of this tier.

Leaks:
  ☐ `FilterMaterialCache` unbounded, no eviction (`crates/core/src/filter.rs:112`). A varying filter (`filter: blur(${n}px)` from a slider) mints a new `Handle<FilterMaterial>` per unique `FilterKey`, never removed → `Assets<FilterMaterial>` grows for the app's lifetime. Add LRU/refcount eviction.
  ☐ `useSharedValue` never frees its Bevy-side shared value on unmount (`js/src/animated.ts:125`). A virtualized list mounting/unmounting rows leaks ids that keep being driven each frame until the next full reset. (Verified 26-07-01: stale-value *reuse* after reset can't happen — `reset()` sends `AnimationCommand::Clear`, `bridge.ts:175` — so this is accumulation-only.)

Cleanup / docs:
  ☐ Register/dedup logic copy-pasted across `message.rs:95`/`request.rs:216`/`event.rs:87` and the three attribute macros; `serializeProps` (`js/src/bridge.ts:316`) hand-duplicates all 11 handler blocks. Collapse each to a shared helper to kill the drift class behind the `HANDLER_PROP_KEYS` finding (adding one handler prop currently means editing 4 places: `HANDLER_KINDS`, the serializeProps chain, `SerializedProps`, `HANDLER_PROP_KEYS`).
  ☐ Merge `raw_spans`/`text_spans` into one map (`crates/core/src/bridge.rs:114`). Two `HashSet<NodeId>`s with a hand-maintained "superset" invariant, kept in lock-step at three sites (insert `reconcile.rs:382`, clear `:174`, remove `bridge.rs:256`); a desync misroutes `Op::UpdateText` with no compile-time guard. One `HashMap<NodeId, SpanKind>` (`RawInherited | InlineStyled`) makes the invariant unrepresentable-when-violated.
  ☐ Stale `export_react_typescript` rustdoc (`crates/core/src/message.rs:217`). The doc example still writes `ui/src/messages.ts`, mentions `generated.ts`, and demonstrates the superseded duplicate-registration pattern ("register the same payloads as the real app") — a user following the crate docs regenerates the wrong filename and reintroduces the hazard the `--export-bindings` convention kills. Rewrite around the single-registration-site + `bevy.ts` convention.
  ☐ Stale comment in `js/src/animated.ts:113` — "A hot reload spins up a fresh isolate, so this resets to 1 naturally" predates the persistent-isolate model (the isolate is never rebuilt on hot reload; `nextSharedId` lives in the vendor bundle and is monotonic). The code is correct; the comment misleads.

Features:
  Interaction & events:
    ☐ Raw `onWheel` — wheel input only drives `overflow: scroll` containers (`crates/core/src/scroll.rs:28`); a non-scroll node (e.g. a zoomable `<canvas>` map) can't receive wheel deltas at all.
    ☐ `cursor` style prop — the window `CursorIcon` is never driven; a `<button>` can't show a pointer hand on hover, `<editableText>` no I-beam. Hover state is already tracked (`HoverState`), so a per-node prop → set-window-cursor system is straightforward.
    ☐ Per-node `onKeyDown`/`onKeyUp` — keyboard is global-only (`bevy.on("keyDown")`, `crates/core/src/keyboard.rs`); scoped key handling (listbox arrow-nav, dialog Esc) forces every widget to subscribe globally and disambiguate by hand. Needs the focus-target infra from the item below.
    ☐ Generic focus event callbacks - `onFocus`/`onBlur` only fire for `<editableText>` today; arbitrary `<node>`/`<button>` aren't focusable (would need `TabIndex`/focus-target infra + keyboard nav to fire `FocusGained`/`FocusLost`).
  Assets & feedback:
    ☐ `<image>` `onLoad`/`onError` — `image_node` (`crates/core/src/ui_map.rs:930`) fire-and-forgets `assets.load(path)`; a bad path renders nothing forever and React is never told, so spinner/fallback UI is impossible. Watch the asset load state and emit per-node events.
  API:
    ☐ Request timeout / cancellation — `request()` (`js/src/bridge.ts:236`) accepts no `AbortSignal`/timeout, so a handler that legitimately takes forever can't be abandoned by the caller. Complements the `Responder`-drop rejection fix (Correctness), which covers the handler-side failure.
  Layout (niche):
    ☐ `direction` (Ltr/Rtl) - no RTL layout.
    ☐ `overflow_clip_margin` (`VisualBox` + margin) and `OverrideClip` (per-node clip opt-out).

Benchmarks and stress tests:
  Framing: the reconciler IS `react-reconciler` (same Fiber engine as web React), so split
  results into (a) apples-to-apples reconcile work — run the SAME component tree through a
  react-dom host and the Bevy host, the delta is pure host/bridge overhead — and (b)
  apples-to-oranges paint (bevy_ui/GPU vs DOM). The headline artifact is a "reconciler is
  identical, here's the host overhead" chart.
  Library-specific:
    ☐ Op-flush hot path (criterion, headless): `serde_v8` deserialize + `apply_js_ops`
      (`crates/core/src/reconcile.rs`) + `ui_map` vs `Vec<Op>` length (10 → 100k). Proves
      the "no JSON strings on the hot path" claim.
    ☐ Mount cost vs tree shape: deep (10k-deep) vs wide (10k siblings) vs balanced.
    ☐ Update amplification: change one prop deep in an N-node tree → assert O(1) ops, not
      O(N). Guards against reconciler/`Op::Update` regressions (relates to the full-`Node`
      rebuild debt above).
    ☐ Keyed-list churn: swap / insert / remove / reorder at scale.
    ☐ End-to-end event round-trip latency (p50/p99 under load): click → `uiEvent` →
      handler → setState → flush → applied. Extend `crates/core/tests/roundtrip.rs` with
      timing. Expect ~1 frame (Bevy→JS is async via tokio mpsc → `op_next_event`).
    ☐ Bevy→React event flood / backpressure: produce events faster than React commits;
      watch the channel grow (ties to the unbounded-channels debt above).
    ☐ Request/response under concurrency: many in-flight `op_request` correlations; verify
      none hang on malformed payloads.
    ☐ Frame-budget interaction (HIGHEST VALUE FIRST): `op_flush` is sync on the Bevy main
      thread and shares the 16.6ms budget with the 3D sim. Measure dropped frames under a
      large flush. Specifically: do world-anchored elements (declared once by React,
      positioned every frame by a Bevy system — NO per-frame bridge traffic) trigger a
      bevy_ui RELAYOUT on position change, or just transform/extract? If transform-only, N
      anchored badges scale almost free; if relayout, that's the cost to fix.
    ☐ Animations engine: N concurrent animations/frame — confirm values are driven
      Rust-side, not round-tripped to JS each frame.
    ☐ Canvas rasterizer: `DrawCmd` throughput/frame.
    ☐ Hot-reload latency + steady-state memory across many reloads (isolate stays alive).
    ☐ Leak/steady-state: frame-time stability; entity count across repeated `selectScene`
      switches (verify `DespawnOnExit` reclaims).
  Cross-framework comparison (port to bevy-react + a vanilla react-dom impl):
    ☐ js-framework-benchmark (krausest) operation set — the industry-standard table:
      create 1k/10k rows, update every 10th, swap, select, remove, clear, append.
    ☐ uibench (localvoid/uibench) — clean reconciler-only comparison, minimal paint.
    ☐ DBMonster / Sierpinski — sustained high-frequency / deep-recursive update cases.
  Expectation (to validate): reconcile ≈ web & faster than RN (Hermes); commit boundary
  faster than DOM mutation, ≈ RN Fabric; layout slower than Blink at high node counts
  (the main risk); world-anchored UI AHEAD of web (web needs per-frame rAF + style writes,
  we do it in Rust/GPU with zero JS).

Verified non-issues (26-07-01 review — don't re-chase):
  Top-level `color`/`fontSize` props are NOT silently dropped — `protocol::Props` has both (`protocol.rs:425`/`:429`, camelCase rename).
  `select_byte_range` can't panic on bad JS selection offsets — parley 0.9 no-ops unless both indices are char boundaries (`editor.rs:749`), and anchor/focus accept any order.
  Unknown request names DO reject the JS promise (`request.rs:262`); malformed payloads too (`:237`).
  Stale shared-value reuse after reset is impossible — `reset()` sends `AnimationCommand::Clear` (`bridge.ts:175` → `animations/lib.rs:178`); only the unmount accumulation leak (tracked above) remains.
  Bundle-watch `!=` mtime compare (`host/native.rs:88`) is fine on ext4 (ns resolution); only coarse filesystems (FAT ~2s) could ever miss a rebuild.

